06072nam a22009975i 9780520966703DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212021cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2020033283  a97805209667037 a10.1525/97805209667032doi  a(DE-B1597)577415  a(OCoLC)1192304508  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aHQ801.82 7aSOC0700002bisacsh04a306.7302851 aCurington, Celeste Vaughan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Dating Divide :bRace and Desire in the Era of Online Romance /cCeleste Vaughan Curington, Ken-Hou Lin, Jennifer Hickes Lundquist. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Tables and Figures -- tIntroduction: Dear Tinder, Guess Who’s Coming to Dinner -- t1. Where Hate Trumps Love: The Birth and Legacy of Antimiscegenation in the United States -- t2. From the Back Porch to the Computer Screen: The Rise of Choice in Courtship -- t3. New Rules? Gendered Online Engagement -- t4. A Privilege Endures: Dating While White in the Era of Online Dating -- t5. The Unique Disadvantage: Dating While Black -- t6. The Asian Experience: Resistance and Complicity -- t7. “Hey, You’re Latin. Do You Like to Dance?”: The Privilege and Disadvantage of Latino/a Daters -- t8. Postracial Multiracialism: A Challenge to the White Racial Frame -- tConclusion: Abolishing the Dating Divide -- tAcknowledgments -- tAppendix: Data and Methods -- tInterviews -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe data behind a distinct form of racism in online datingThe Dating Divide is the first comprehensive look at ";digital-sexual racism,"; a distinct form of racism that is mediated and amplified through the impersonal and anonymous context of online dating. Drawing on large-scale behavioral data from a mainstream dating website, extensive archival research, and more than seventy-five in-depth interviews with daters of diverse racial backgrounds and sexual identities, Curington, Lundquist, and Lin illustrate how the seemingly open space of the internet interacts with the loss of social inhibition in cyberspace contexts, fostering openly expressed forms of sexual racism that are rarely exposed in face-to-face encounters. The Dating Divide is a fascinating look at how a contemporary conflux of individualization, consumerism, and the proliferation of digital technologies has given rise to a unique form of gendered racism in the era of swiping right—or left.The internet is often heralded as an equalizer, a seemingly level playing field, but the digital world also acts as an extension of and platform for the insidious prejudices and divisive impulses that affect social politics in the ";real"; world. Shedding light on how every click, swipe, or message can be linked to the history of racism and courtship in the United States, this compelling study uses data to show the racial biases at play in digital dating spaces.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aOnline dating. 0aRacism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Race & Ethnic Relations.2bisacsh  aapps.  aattraction.  abumble.  aculture.  adata.  adesire.  adigital.  adiscrimination.  afilter.  ahierarchy.  ahinge.  ainequality.  ainternet.  ainterracial relationships.  aintersectionality.  alove.  amodern.  amyths.  aoccidentalism.  aonline.  aorientalism.  apolitical.  apower.  apreferences.  aracism.  asuperiority.  asystemic.  atinder.1 aLin, Ken-Hou, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLundquist, Jennifer Hickes, eauthor.4aut4http://